\begin_body

\begin_layout Title
Statistics and Nuclear Events
\end_layout

\begin_layout Author
Atul Singh Arora, Prashansa Gupta, Vivek Sagar
\end_layout

\begin_layout Date
November 14, 2014
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Introduction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Here we attempt to verify the popular relation between Poisson distributions
 and distribution of radioactive decays.
 We first discuss the mathematical construction of the distribution and
 then demonstrate experimentally that it obeys the aforesaid distribution
 and in the limit of large 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 (defined in the following section) the distribution becomes normal.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Theory
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consider an experiment when a Bernoulli trial is repeated 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 times.
 The probabilty of obtaining a success in a single trial is 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

.
 The probability of obtaining exactly 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 successes (and 
\begin_inset Formula $n-k$
\end_inset

 failures) is given by the Binomial distribution: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
b(k,n,p)=C_{k}^{n}p^{k}(1-p)^{n-k}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the situations when 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 is small and 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 is large such that the product 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda=np$
\end_inset

 is of moderate magnitude, 
\begin_inset Formula $b(0,n,p)$
\end_inset

 can be approximated as 
\begin_inset Formula $e^{-\lambda}$
\end_inset

 since,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
log(b(0,n,p))=nlog(1-\frac{\lambda}{n})=-\lambda-\frac{\lambda^{2}}{2n}...\approx-\lambda
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Also,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{b(k-1,n,p)}{b(k,n,p)}=\frac{(n-k+1)p}{kq}=\frac{\lambda-(k-1)p}{kq}\approx\frac{\lambda}{k}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $b(k,n,p)$
\end_inset

 can thus, be approximated as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
a(k,\lambda)=\frac{\lambda^{k}}{k!}e^{-\lambda}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

 This is called the Poission approximation to the Binomial distribution.
 
\begin_inset Formula $a(k,\lambda)$
\end_inset

 can also be considered as a distribution since 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{k}a(k,\lambda)=1.$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now imagine a sequence of random events occuring in time, such as radioactive
 disintegrations of a sample.
 Each disintegration can be considered as a point on the time axis.
 If we partition the unit time interval into 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 segments, the width of each segment being small enough so that the possibility
 of obtaining two decays in a single segment is negligble.
 The probability of obtaining exactly 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 decays in 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 segments is then 
\begin_inset Formula $b(k,n,p_{n})$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{n}$
\end_inset

 is the probability that an arbitarary segment of time of length 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{1}{n}$
\end_inset

 observes a radioactive disintegration.
 Let us now ask, what is the probability of obtaining no decay in the unit
 time? The answer is 
\begin_inset Formula $b(0,n,p_{n})=(1-p_{n})^{n}.$
\end_inset

 In the limit 
\begin_inset Formula $n\rightarrow\infty,$
\end_inset

 the value 
\begin_inset Formula $b(0,n,p_{n})$
\end_inset

 approaches a finite value only if 
\begin_inset Formula $np_{n}\rightarrow\lambda,$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 being some real number.
 This can be checked by taking the 
\begin_inset Formula $log$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $b(0,n,p_{n})$
\end_inset

 and Taylor expanding 
\begin_inset Formula $log(1-p_{n})$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Thus, the phenonmenon can be approximated using the Poission distribution.
 The probability of obtaining 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 decays in a unit time is thus 
\begin_inset Formula $a(k,\lambda).$
\end_inset

 It is often important to ask, what is the probability of obtaining 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 decays in 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 time, in which case one can again partition the interval into segments
 of length 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{1}{n}.$
\end_inset

 In this case, the number of segments will become 
\begin_inset Formula $nt.$
\end_inset

 Thus, 
\begin_inset Formula $np=\lambda$
\end_inset

 in the equation 
\begin_inset Formula $(1)$
\end_inset

 should be replaced with 
\begin_inset Formula $npt=\lambda t.$
\end_inset

 Thus, the probability of obtaining 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 decays in time 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $a(k,\lambda t).$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We have done the experiment with Cs-137 (with large 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

) and with Tl (with smaller 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

) 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Temp
\end_layout

